import{a as e}from"./chunk-332OXTVJ.js";import"./chunk-IFGU66OU.js";var t={meta:e,sections:[{id:"overview",title:"Overview",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Netflix is a global subscription video-on-demand (VOD) service streaming to **260M+ members** across 190+ countries. At peak it serves a double-digit percentage of global internet traffic. The core challenge is delivering high-bitrate video with **low startup latency** and **minimal rebuffering** to a huge, geographically distributed audience \u2014 while keeping the catalog, recommendations, and billing systems highly available."},{type:"callout",variant:"info",title:"The big idea",body:"Netflix separates a **control plane** (running on AWS: auth, metadata, recommendations, steering) from a **data plane** (Open Connect, its own purpose-built CDN that pushes video bytes as close to viewers as possible). Almost all bandwidth flows through the CDN, never through AWS."},{type:"image",src:"assets/diagrams/netflix-playback.svg",alt:"Netflix playback path: client steered by AWS control plane, video served by Open Connect CDN filled by the encoding pipeline.",caption:'High-level playback path. The control plane "steers" the client to the best CDN server; bytes then flow from Open Connect.'}]},{id:"functional-requirements",title:"Functional Requirements",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"We scope the interview to the streaming core rather than every Netflix feature."},{type:"bestPractices",title:"In scope",practices:["Browse and search the catalog of titles.","Stream a title with **adaptive bitrate** based on device and network.","Resume playback from where the user left off (continue watching).","Personalized homepage / recommendations.","Multiple device profiles per account."]},{type:"callout",variant:"note",title:"Out of scope (call this out explicitly)",body:"Content production, DRM internals, payments/billing details, and the ML model training pipeline. Mentioning what you are *not* designing keeps the discussion focused."}]},{id:"non-functional-requirements",title:"Non-Functional Requirements",blocks:[{type:"prosCons",title:"Prioritizing the qualities",pros:["High availability for playback (target 99.99%).","Low startup latency (time-to-first-frame < 1s).","Smooth playback: rebuffer ratio as close to 0 as possible.","Read-heavy scalability for catalog & recommendations.","Global low latency via edge delivery."],cons:["Strong consistency is NOT required for most reads (eventual is fine).","User-facing write QPS (ratings, my-list) is modest; **playback heartbeats and QoS telemetry** are enormous and must be async via Kafka.","Exact real-time view counts are not critical."]},{type:"callout",variant:"tip",title:"CAP framing",body:'Netflix overwhelmingly chooses **Availability + Partition tolerance (AP)** for member-facing reads. A stale "Continue Watching" row is acceptable; an unavailable home screen is not.'}]},{id:"capacity-estimation",title:"Capacity Estimation",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Back-of-the-envelope numbers anchor every later decision. Assume **250M** members, each watching **2 hours/day** on average."},{type:"metrics",items:[{label:"Daily watch hours",value:"~500M hrs",hint:"250M \xD7 2h"},{label:"Avg bitrate",value:"~5 Mbps",hint:"HD, adaptive"},{label:"Peak concurrent streams",value:"~50\u201360M",hint:"evening peaks"},{label:"Peak egress",value:"> 250 Tbps",hint:"served by CDN"}]},{type:"markdown",value:"Peak egress dwarfs anything a general-purpose cloud could economically serve, which is *why* Netflix built Open Connect. A quick estimate of peak bandwidth:"},{type:"math",display:!0,tex:"B_{peak} = C_{peak} \\times R_{avg} = 5\\times10^{7}\\ \\text{streams} \\times 5\\times10^{6}\\ \\text{bps} = 2.5\\times10^{14}\\ \\text{bps} = 250\\ \\text{Tbps}",caption:"Peak egress bandwidth \u2248 concurrent streams \xD7 average bitrate."},{type:"markdown",value:"Storage for the catalog is also large. A single popular title is encoded into **dozens** of (codec \xD7 resolution \xD7 bitrate) variants, plus audio tracks and subtitles, easily reaching **terabytes per title** across the full ladder."}]},{id:"high-level-architecture",title:"High-Level Architecture",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Requests hit an edge gateway (Zuul) which routes to backend microservices. Heavy reads are absorbed by EVCache. Video never traverses this path \u2014 it is served by Open Connect Appliances (OCAs) embedded inside ISP networks."},{type:"mermaid",caption:"Control plane on AWS + data plane on Open Connect.",definition:`flowchart TD
  Client["Client (TV / Mobile / Web)"] -->|API| Zuul["Zuul API Gateway"]
  Zuul --> Playback["Playback / Steering Service"]
  Zuul --> Catalog["Catalog Service"]
  Zuul --> Reco["Recommendation Service"]
  Catalog --> EVCache[("EVCache")]
  Reco --> EVCache
  Catalog --> Cassandra[("Cassandra")]
  Playback --> Steering["Steering: pick best OCA"]
  Steering --> Client
  Client -->|video bytes| OCA["Open Connect Appliance @ ISP"]
  Pipeline["Encoding Pipeline"] -->|fill overnight| OCA`},{type:"architectureCard",title:"Open Connect Appliance (OCA)",description:"Custom storage server placed inside ISP data centers and internet exchanges. Pre-loaded with the most popular titles during off-peak hours so playback is a short, fast hop from the viewer.",icon:"server",tags:["CDN","edge","pre-positioning"]},{type:"architectureCard",title:"Zuul API Gateway",description:"Dynamic edge routing, load shedding, authentication, and request-level resiliency (retries, fallbacks) in front of hundreds of microservices.",icon:"network",tags:["gateway","routing","resilience"]}]},{id:"api-design",title:"API Design",blocks:[{type:"apiTable",title:"Core playback & catalog endpoints",endpoints:[{method:"GET",path:"/v1/home",description:"Personalized rows for the home screen",auth:!0},{method:"GET",path:"/v1/titles/{id}",description:"Title metadata + available streams",auth:!0},{method:"GET",path:"/v1/search?q=",description:"Search the catalog",auth:!0},{method:"POST",path:"/v1/playback/start",description:"Begin a session; returns manifest + steering",auth:!0},{method:"POST",path:"/v1/playback/heartbeat",description:"Report progress + QoS metrics",auth:!0},{method:"GET",path:"/v1/continue-watching",description:"Resume positions per profile",auth:!0}]},{type:"markdown",value:"A `playback/start` response hands the client a **manifest** (the ABR ladder) and a ranked list of OCA URLs to stream from:"},{type:"code",language:"json",filename:"playback-start-response.json",code:`{
  "sessionId": "a1b2c3",
  "title": { "id": "81234567", "duration": 5400 },
  "manifest": {
    "video": [
      { "bitrate": 560000,  "resolution": "480p",  "codec": "h264" },
      { "bitrate": 1750000, "resolution": "720p",  "codec": "h264" },
      { "bitrate": 4300000, "resolution": "1080p", "codec": "vp9" },
      { "bitrate": 8000000, "resolution": "2160p", "codec": "av1" }
    ],
    "audio": [{ "lang": "en", "bitrate": 192000 }]
  },
  "steering": [
    "https://oca-12.isp.net/stream/...",
    "https://oca-08.isp.net/stream/..."
  ]
}`}]},{id:"database-design",title:"Database Design",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:'Different data has different access patterns, so Netflix uses **polyglot persistence**. The "viewing history" / "continue watching" data is write-once-read-many and partition-friendly \u2014 a great fit for Cassandra.'},{type:"code",language:"sql",filename:"viewing_history.cql",highlightLines:[2,6],code:`-- Cassandra: partition by profile so a member's history is one fast read.
CREATE TABLE viewing_history (
  profile_id   uuid,
  title_id     bigint,
  position_sec int,
  updated_at   timestamp,
  PRIMARY KEY ((profile_id), title_id)   -- partition key + clustering key
) WITH CLUSTERING ORDER BY (title_id ASC);`},{type:"table",caption:"Data store chosen per workload.",headers:["Data","Store","Why"],rows:[["Viewing history / progress","Cassandra","High write volume, partition by profile, AP"],["Title metadata","Cassandra + EVCache","Read-heavy, cacheable, rarely changes"],["Recommendations (precomputed)","EVCache / Cassandra","Served fast, regenerated offline"],["Member / billing","MySQL (RDS)","Transactional, strong consistency"],["Search index","Elasticsearch","Full-text + typeahead"]]}]},{id:"caching-strategy",title:"Caching Strategy",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"There are two distinct caches: **EVCache** (an in-memory, Memcached-based tier for metadata/recommendations) and the **CDN itself** (caching the actual video bytes)."},{type:"callout",variant:"info",title:"EVCache",body:"A sharded, replicated Memcached layer. Writes fan out to multiple zones so a single AZ failure does not cause a cold cache. Reads are local-zone first for single-digit-millisecond latency."},{type:"code",language:"java",filename:"CatalogService.java",highlightLines:[9,10,11,12],code:`@Service
public class CatalogService {

  private final EVCache cache;       // cache-aside
  private final TitleRepository repo; // Cassandra

  public Title getTitle(long id) {
    String key = "title:" + id;
    Title cached = cache.get(key, Title.class);
    if (cached != null) {
      return cached;                  // hot path: served from memory
    }
    Title title = repo.findById(id);  // miss: read-through to Cassandra
    cache.set(key, title, TTL_1_HOUR);
    return title;
  }
}`},{type:"bestPractices",title:"Caching best practices applied here",practices:["Use **cache-aside** for read-heavy, change-rarely data like titles.","Replicate cache writes across AZs to avoid thundering-herd on failover.","Set TTLs and add jitter to prevent synchronized expiry stampedes.","Pre-warm caches for newly released, anticipated-hot titles."]}]},{id:"load-balancing",title:"Load Balancing",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Load balancing happens at several layers: DNS-based geo steering, AWS ELB/ALB in front of services, and Zuul + Eureka for **client-side, service-to-service** load balancing (via Ribbon)."},{type:"mermaid",caption:"Request distribution layers.",definition:`flowchart LR
  DNS["Geo DNS"] --> ALB["AWS ALB"]
  ALB --> Zuul["Zuul (edge)"]
  Zuul --> Eureka["Eureka (service discovery)"]
  Eureka --> S1["Service A inst 1"]
  Eureka --> S2["Service A inst 2"]
  Eureka --> S3["Service A inst 3"]`},{type:"callout",variant:"tip",title:"Steering \u2260 load balancing",body:"For video, the *steering* service picks an OCA based on health, fill status, and network proximity \u2014 not just least-connections. It is a routing decision optimized for throughput and locality."}]},{id:"storage",title:"Storage",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"The encoding pipeline outputs many variants per title. Masters and mezzanines live in **S3**; the playable, pre-positioned copies live on **OCA disks** at the edge."},{type:"timeline",items:[{title:"Ingest",description:"Studio delivers a high-quality mezzanine master.",meta:"S3"},{title:"Transcode",description:"Parallel chunked encoding into the full ABR ladder (per-title optimized).",meta:"pipeline"},{title:"Package",description:"Segment + apply DRM, generate manifests.",meta:"pipeline"},{title:"Pre-position",description:"Push popular titles to OCAs overnight during off-peak.",meta:"Open Connect"},{title:"Serve",description:"Client streams segments from the nearest healthy OCA.",meta:"edge"}]}]},{id:"message-queues",title:"Message Queues",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:`Playback heartbeats, QoS telemetry, and viewing events are produced at enormous volume. They flow through **Kafka** (Netflix's Keystone pipeline) and are consumed by analytics, the recommendation pipeline, and the "continue watching" updater \u2014 decoupling producers from slow consumers.`},{type:"code",language:"python",filename:"heartbeat_consumer.py",code:`from kafka import KafkaConsumer
import json

consumer = KafkaConsumer(
    "playback.heartbeat",
    bootstrap_servers=["keystone:9092"],
    group_id="continue-watching-updater",
    value_deserializer=lambda m: json.loads(m.decode("utf-8")),
)

for message in consumer:
    event = message.value
    # Idempotent upsert of the resume position into Cassandra.
    upsert_progress(event["profile_id"], event["title_id"], event["position_sec"])`},{type:"callout",variant:"warning",title:"Make consumers idempotent",body:"At-least-once delivery means duplicates happen. Keying the upsert on `(profile_id, title_id)` makes reprocessing safe."}]},{id:"communication-flow",title:"Communication Flow",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:'A full "press play" sequence, end to end:'},{type:"mermaid",caption:"Sequence for starting playback.",definition:`sequenceDiagram
  participant C as Client
  participant Z as Zuul
  participant P as Playback Svc
  participant S as Steering
  participant O as OCA (CDN)
  C->>Z: POST /playback/start
  Z->>P: authorize + create session
  P->>S: which OCA?
  S-->>P: ranked OCA list
  P-->>C: manifest + steering URLs
  C->>O: GET segment (lowest safe bitrate)
  O-->>C: video bytes
  C->>O: GET next segments (ramp up bitrate)
  C->>Z: heartbeat (progress + QoS)`}]},{id:"scaling-strategy",title:"Scaling Strategy",blocks:[{type:"bestPractices",practices:["**Scale reads horizontally** with EVCache + Cassandra replicas; the home screen is almost entirely cache hits.","**Offload all bandwidth** to Open Connect so AWS scaling is about requests-per-second, not gigabits.","**Precompute** recommendations offline (Spark) and serve them as a fast key lookup.","**Autoscale** stateless microservices on AWS by RPS and latency.","**Pre-position** content to flatten peak-hour origin load."]}]},{id:"consistency",title:"Consistency",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Member-facing data is **eventually consistent**. Cassandra is tuned with quorum or even ONE for some reads where speed beats freshness. Billing/membership uses strongly consistent MySQL."},{type:"featureComparison",caption:"Consistency level by data type.",columns:["Strong","Eventual"],rows:[{feature:"Billing & subscription",values:[!0,!1]},{feature:"Viewing progress",values:[!1,!0]},{feature:"Recommendations",values:[!1,!0]},{feature:"Catalog metadata",values:[!1,!0]},{feature:"Account login",values:[!0,!1]}]}]},{id:"availability",title:"Availability",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Netflix engineers for failure as the normal case. The **Simian Army** (notably Chaos Monkey) randomly kills instances in production to prove the system degrades gracefully. Services use Hystrix-style circuit breakers and **fallbacks**: if recommendations fail, show a non-personalized but still useful row instead of an error."},{type:"callout",variant:"summary",title:"Graceful degradation",body:"Every dependency has a fallback. A failure in a non-critical service should never take down the play button."},{type:"youtube",videoId:"CZ3wIuvmHeM",title:"System Design deep dive (illustrative embed)"}]},{id:"partitioning",title:"Partitioning",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Cassandra partitions by a hash of the partition key. Choosing `profile_id` as the partition key for viewing history keeps each member's reads on a single partition while spreading load evenly across the ring."},{type:"callout",variant:"warning",title:"Avoid hot partitions",body:'Partitioning a global "most watched" counter by `title_id` would create a hot partition for a viral title. Shard such counters (e.g. `title_id:bucket`) and aggregate.'}]},{id:"sharding",title:"Sharding",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Cassandra handles sharding transparently via consistent hashing across the token ring, so adding nodes rebalances data automatically. For the relational membership data, sharding is by member id when a single primary can no longer keep up."},{type:"mermaid",caption:"Consistent hashing token ring.",definition:`flowchart LR
  K1["key: profile A"] --> N1["Node 1 (tokens 0-85)"]
  K2["key: profile B"] --> N2["Node 2 (tokens 86-170)"]
  K3["key: profile C"] --> N3["Node 3 (tokens 171-255)"]`}]},{id:"replication",title:"Replication",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Cassandra replicates each partition to **RF=3** replicas, typically one per availability zone. Netflix runs **multi-region active-active**: members can be served from another AWS region if their home region fails, with data replicated cross-region."},{type:"prosCons",title:"Active-active multi-region",pros:["Survives an entire region outage.","Lower latency by routing to the nearest region.","No cold standby waste."],cons:["Cross-region replication lag \u2192 conflicts to resolve.","Operationally complex (data + traffic steering).","Higher cost than single region."]}]},{id:"fault-tolerance",title:"Fault Tolerance",blocks:[{type:"bestPractices",practices:["**Circuit breakers** stop cascading failures when a dependency is slow.","**Bulkheads / thread pools** isolate one slow dependency from the rest.","**Timeouts + retries with backoff + jitter** on every network call.","**Fallbacks** return degraded-but-useful responses.","**Chaos engineering** continuously validates all of the above in prod."]},{type:"expandable",title:"Example: a Hystrix-style command with fallback",blocks:[{type:"code",language:"java",filename:"GetRecommendationsCommand.java",code:`public class GetRecommendationsCommand extends HystrixCommand<List<Title>> {
  protected List<Title> run() {
    return recoClient.fetch(profileId); // may time out / fail
  }

  @Override
  protected List<Title> getFallback() {
    // Degrade gracefully: trending titles instead of personalized ones.
    return trendingCache.topN(20);
  }
}`}]}]},{id:"trade-offs",title:"Trade-offs",blocks:[{type:"table",caption:"Key decisions and what they cost.",headers:["Decision","Gain","Cost"],rows:[["Build own CDN (Open Connect)","Massive bandwidth savings, control","Huge capex + operational scope"],["Eventual consistency","Availability + low latency","Occasional stale reads"],["Microservices","Independent scaling/deploys","Distributed-system complexity"],["Pre-positioning content","Flat peak load, fast start","Storage cost, prediction needed"],["Polyglot persistence","Right tool per workload","More systems to operate"]]}]},{id:"technology-choices",title:"Technology Choices",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"A representative slice of the stack and the role each plays:"},{type:"table",headers:["Concern","Technology"],rows:[["Edge gateway","Zuul"],["Service discovery","Eureka"],["Caching","EVCache (Memcached)"],["Primary NoSQL","Apache Cassandra"],["Streaming/eventing","Apache Kafka (Keystone)"],["Search","Elasticsearch"],["Offline compute","Apache Spark"],["CDN","Open Connect (custom)"],["Resilience","Hystrix / resilience4j"]]},{type:"callout",variant:"note",title:"Infra as code",body:"Immutable AMIs baked with Aminator and deployed via Spinnaker give fast, repeatable, rollback-friendly releases."},{type:"code",language:"yaml",filename:"playback-service.deploy.yaml",code:`service: playback
strategy: red-black        # zero-downtime, instant rollback
regions: [us-east-1, us-west-2, eu-west-1]
autoscaling:
  metric: rps
  target: 1200
  min: 12
  max: 400
healthCheck:
  path: /health
  unhealthyThreshold: 3`}]},{id:"interview-questions",title:"Interview Questions",blocks:[{type:"interviewQa",items:[{question:"Why did Netflix build its own CDN instead of using a commercial one?",answer:"At Netflix's scale (>250 Tbps peak), commercial CDN costs are enormous and Netflix needs deep control over **placement** (inside ISPs), **fill scheduling**, and **steering**. Open Connect lets them pre-position popular content directly in ISP networks, cutting transit costs and improving quality."},{question:"How does adaptive bitrate (ABR) streaming work?",answer:"Video is encoded at multiple bitrates and split into short segments (2\u201310s). The client measures throughput and buffer health, then requests the next segment at the highest bitrate it can sustain \u2014 ramping up on good networks and down to avoid rebuffering."},{question:'How would you design "Continue Watching"?',answer:"Clients emit periodic heartbeats with the playback position. These go through Kafka to an **idempotent** consumer that upserts `(profile_id, title_id) -> position` in Cassandra. Reads are a single-partition lookup, optionally cached in EVCache."},{question:"What happens when the recommendation service is down?",answer:"A circuit breaker trips and a **fallback** returns non-personalized content (e.g. trending/most-popular). The user still gets a usable home screen \u2014 graceful degradation over hard failure."},{question:"Throughput-based vs buffer-based ABR \u2014 which and why?",answer:"**Throughput-based** picks bitrate from recent download speed \u2014 simple but can oscillate. **Buffer-based** (e.g. BOLA) keys off buffer occupancy to avoid rebuffering. Production players usually **hybridize**: buffer health for stability, throughput as a cap \u2014 Netflix-style ABR optimizes for fewer stalls over peak sharpness."},{question:"How does Open Connect decide which titles to pre-position?",answer:"Rank by **predicted local demand**: popularity, regional catalogs, time-of-day, new releases, and ISP-specific watch patterns. Fill OCAs off-peak with the working set that covers most byte-hours, and rely on mid-peak fill / parent caches for long-tail misses."},{question:"Multi-device continue-watching consistency?",answer:"Devices publish position heartbeats; the service **upserts** the latest `(profile, title) \u2192 position` with event-time / version so out-of-order updates do not rewind progress. Reads are eventually consistent across devices \u2014 a phone may lag a TV by seconds; conflict policy is usually **latest write wins** with a small grace for near-simultaneous play."},{question:"What happens when an AWS region fails?",answer:"Member **control plane** fails over to another active region (DNS/steering, replicated stateful services). Playback already steered to **Open Connect** keeps serving cached bits; new manifests/licenses retry against healthy regional endpoints. Chaos testing and multi-region active-active are how this is rehearsed."},{question:"Why does video traffic largely bypass AWS?",answer:"Video bytes dominate cost and bandwidth. **Open Connect** appliances inside ISP networks deliver segments locally so Netflix avoids hauling petabytes through AWS egress. AWS hosts the **control plane** (UI, personalization, licensing); the **data plane** is the CDN."}]}]},{id:"references",title:"References",blocks:[{type:"references",items:[{label:"Netflix Open Connect",url:"https://openconnect.netflix.com/",source:"Netflix"},{label:"Netflix Tech Blog",url:"https://netflixtechblog.com/",source:"Medium"},{label:"Zuul: edge service",url:"https://github.com/Netflix/zuul",source:"GitHub"},{label:"EVCache",url:"https://github.com/Netflix/EVCache",source:"GitHub"},{label:"Chaos Engineering / Simian Army",url:"https://netflixtechblog.com/the-netflix-simian-army-16e57fbab116",source:"Netflix"}]}]},{id:"summary",title:"Summary",blocks:[{type:"callout",variant:"summary",title:"Key takeaways",body:`1. **Split control plane (AWS) from data plane (Open Connect)** \u2014 bytes go through the CDN, logic through microservices.
2. **Pre-position popular content** at the edge to flatten peak load and minimize startup latency.
3. **Embrace eventual consistency** for member-facing reads to maximize availability.
4. **Design for failure**: circuit breakers, fallbacks, multi-region active-active, and chaos testing.
5. **Cache aggressively** (EVCache) and **precompute** recommendations offline.`}]}]},i=t;export{i as default};
